1
00:00:08,180 --> 00:00:13,530
Tonight, James experiences the sheer
grunt of a Chevrolet Silverado.

2
00:00:13,580 --> 00:00:15,890
I go airborne in a Ford Velociraptor.

3
00:00:15,940 --> 00:00:18,740
And Richard Hammond
carries some wood.

4
00:00:22,740 --> 00:00:25,370
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

5
00:00:25,420 --> 00:00:27,170
Hello!

6
00:00:27,220 --> 00:00:29,570
Hello, and good evening.

7
00:00:29,620 --> 00:00:31,220
Hello. Now...

8
00:00:33,060 --> 00:00:37,330
Thank you very much. A while
back I heard that Lexus

9
00:00:37,380 --> 00:00:40,290
was working on a car called the RCF.

10
00:00:40,340 --> 00:00:44,970
It would be a two-door coupe
with a five-litre V8 engine

11
00:00:45,020 --> 00:00:50,210
and it would take on the smaller
AMG Mercs and M-powered BMWs.

12
00:00:50,260 --> 00:00:51,970
And I was very excited.

13
00:00:52,020 --> 00:00:55,490
I couldn't wait to give it
a spanking round our track.

14
00:00:55,540 --> 00:00:57,530
And now I have.

15
00:00:57,580 --> 00:00:59,940
DRAMATIC MUSIC

16
00:01:07,580 --> 00:01:11,260
I expected it to be
sharp... but violent.

17
00:01:19,260 --> 00:01:21,130
Raw, but civilised.

18
00:01:22,340 --> 00:01:24,700
Powerful, but controlled.

19
00:01:29,140 --> 00:01:32,060
I expected a bank of Tokyo hi tech...

20
00:01:34,140 --> 00:01:36,940
.. with the exhaust
bark of a mad dog.

21
00:01:39,140 --> 00:01:43,020
But actually it turned
out to be fat and useless.

22
00:01:45,660 --> 00:01:47,090
REALLY fat.

23
00:01:47,140 --> 00:01:50,780
With two people on board,
it weighs nearly two tonnes.

24
00:01:52,500 --> 00:01:57,890
So look what happens when you put
it in a drag race with a BMW M4.

25
00:01:57,940 --> 00:02:00,370
ENGINES REVVING

26
00:02:00,420 --> 00:02:02,530
Three... two... one...

27
00:02:02,580 --> 00:02:03,740
go!

28
00:02:07,580 --> 00:02:10,660
The BMW just walks away.

29
00:02:13,140 --> 00:02:18,100
I have 40 more horsepower than
he does and I'm being humiliated!

30
00:02:23,980 --> 00:02:27,700
The enormous weight means it's
no good in the corners, either.

31
00:02:29,340 --> 00:02:32,850
I have got many, many
different settings in here

32
00:02:32,900 --> 00:02:37,650
and I've got G-SHIFT control,
whatever that is.

33
00:02:37,700 --> 00:02:40,090
And VDIM.

34
00:02:40,140 --> 00:02:45,450
I've got STANDARD, ECO, SPORT S,

35
00:02:45,500 --> 00:02:49,090
SPORT S+, something called SLALOM.

36
00:02:49,140 --> 00:02:51,850
Doesn't matter which one you select,

37
00:02:51,900 --> 00:02:54,330
you just get yards and yards

38
00:02:54,380 --> 00:02:56,530
of wearisome understeer

39
00:02:56,580 --> 00:03:00,610
and then a lot of
electronic interference.

40
00:03:00,660 --> 00:03:03,850
There is, however, another
setting in the RCF

41
00:03:03,900 --> 00:03:06,170
which makes it even worse.

42
00:03:06,220 --> 00:03:10,650
If you put it in SPORT+ and
then push this button here...

43
00:03:10,700 --> 00:03:13,130
Look! I'm now in EXPERT mode.

44
00:03:13,180 --> 00:03:14,970
It says it there.

45
00:03:15,020 --> 00:03:18,410
I have told the car
that I am an expert.

46
00:03:18,460 --> 00:03:22,060
I don't need the electronic
stuff, I can manage.

47
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:26,740
Oh, God!

48
00:03:31,340 --> 00:03:35,220
Lurchy. That's the word I'm
looking for there. Lurchy.

49
00:03:40,100 --> 00:03:43,170
It's really struggling
to deal with the weight.

50
00:03:43,220 --> 00:03:44,620
Come on!

51
00:03:46,420 --> 00:03:48,560
Why are you doing that?!

52
00:03:49,020 --> 00:03:52,060
I'm an expert, look. Look how
I'm going round this corner.

53
00:03:53,380 --> 00:03:56,380
That's an expert use of the
- Oh, I'm on the grass.

54
00:03:57,860 --> 00:04:02,490
The simple truth of the matter
is you can put John Prescott

55
00:04:02,540 --> 00:04:04,970
in a pair of running shoes...

56
00:04:05,020 --> 00:04:07,560
but it won't make him an athlete.

57
00:04:08,380 --> 00:04:10,490
I really don't like this car.

58
00:04:10,540 --> 00:04:13,370
I don't like the way it looks,
I don't like the way it goes,

59
00:04:13,420 --> 00:04:15,820
I don't like the way it feels.

60
00:04:16,580 --> 00:04:18,410
But what really annoys me,

61
00:04:18,460 --> 00:04:20,770
what really gets my goat

62
00:04:20,820 --> 00:04:25,380
is that I know Lexus
can do so much better.

63
00:04:35,260 --> 00:04:38,140
A few years ago, they
gave us the LFA.

64
00:04:40,740 --> 00:04:45,460
A car which, I'll admit, has
many faults and irritations.

65
00:04:49,420 --> 00:04:54,450
The seat belt, for example, is
incredibly difficult to do up. Um...

66
00:04:54,500 --> 00:04:57,690
There are no cup holders, it's
impossible to plug your telephone

67
00:04:57,740 --> 00:05:00,370
or whatever into the stereo system,

68
00:05:00,420 --> 00:05:03,090
and the fuel tank is the size
of a disposable lighter,

69
00:05:03,140 --> 00:05:05,570
which means you have to fill
up every five minutes,

70
00:05:05,620 --> 00:05:07,530
and then you have to get out,

71
00:05:07,580 --> 00:05:10,730
and then it takes you a week
to do your seat belt up again.

72
00:05:10,780 --> 00:05:13,370
I still haven't done it!

73
00:05:13,420 --> 00:05:16,290
It's like giving myself
a prostate exam.

74
00:05:17,780 --> 00:05:21,770
But these little things
pale into insignificance

75
00:05:21,820 --> 00:05:25,500
when you unleash its
astonishing V10 engine.

76
00:05:26,860 --> 00:05:28,780
ENGINE REVVING

77
00:05:35,980 --> 00:05:39,900
It produces 552 horsepower.

78
00:05:41,260 --> 00:05:45,860
That means 0 to 60 in 3.7 seconds.

79
00:05:56,900 --> 00:06:00,570
It also means a top speed of 202,

80
00:06:00,620 --> 00:06:05,210
and even more amazingly, it
revs from idle to the red line

81
00:06:05,260 --> 00:06:09,660
in an almost unbelievable
0.6 of a second.

82
00:06:15,900 --> 00:06:19,530
But the best thing is the noise.

83
00:06:19,580 --> 00:06:21,970
ENGINE ROARS

84
00:06:22,020 --> 00:06:25,330
It sounds baleful, it sounds
like a wild animal that's...

85
00:06:25,380 --> 00:06:27,320
sad about something.

86
00:06:29,220 --> 00:06:32,010
"Oh, nooooooooo!

87
00:06:32,060 --> 00:06:34,250
"I've got my paw stuck!

88
00:06:34,300 --> 00:06:36,010
"Ow!

89
00:06:36,060 --> 00:06:38,330
"Ow!

90
00:06:38,380 --> 00:06:40,130
"Ow!"

91
00:06:40,180 --> 00:06:44,210
This is what I was looking
for in the new Lexus,

92
00:06:44,260 --> 00:06:49,020
a sense that the engine is actually
alive, that it's a sentient being.

93
00:06:50,540 --> 00:06:53,540
And there was more I
was looking for, too.

94
00:06:54,980 --> 00:06:58,210
The LFA does not have
an EXPERT facility,

95
00:06:58,260 --> 00:07:01,420
or a G-SHIFT thing, or VDIM.

96
00:07:04,980 --> 00:07:08,780
It corners well because
it's well engineered.

97
00:07:13,340 --> 00:07:15,780
And it's light - very light.

98
00:07:23,780 --> 00:07:25,700
TYRES SCREECH

99
00:07:26,780 --> 00:07:29,820
And I love the way that it
feels so violent and raw.

100
00:07:37,220 --> 00:07:40,260
This car is simply out of this world.

101
00:07:45,260 --> 00:07:47,930
And look at the
difference in styling.

102
00:07:47,980 --> 00:07:52,170
See how one looks like that stupid
food that's drizzled in jus

103
00:07:52,220 --> 00:07:54,010
and served on a bed of stupid beans

104
00:07:54,060 --> 00:07:57,890
to idiots in over-priced restaurants.

105
00:07:57,940 --> 00:08:01,740
And the other is as simple as
a freshly picked blackberry.

106
00:08:04,820 --> 00:08:10,650
I know that this costs five or
six times more than the new RCF,

107
00:08:10,700 --> 00:08:14,410
and I know it's full of carbon fibre
and all sorts of clever engineering

108
00:08:14,460 --> 00:08:17,610
that you can't reasonably
expect to find

109
00:08:17,660 --> 00:08:20,290
further down the fiscal food chain,

110
00:08:20,340 --> 00:08:25,810
but surely they could have captured
the spirit of this car, the essence,

111
00:08:25,860 --> 00:08:30,170
its soul, and transplanted
that into the RCF.

112
00:08:30,220 --> 00:08:32,090
Surely they could.

113
00:08:34,300 --> 00:08:37,490
Or maybe they couldn't.

114
00:08:37,540 --> 00:08:40,370
Maybe the LFA is so good,

115
00:08:40,420 --> 00:08:44,780
not even the people who made
it know how to make it again.

116
00:08:50,140 --> 00:08:52,620
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

117
00:08:55,820 --> 00:08:59,690
~ Um, you said you were going
to give it a spanking.
~ Yeah.

118
00:08:59,740 --> 00:09:01,330
But you gave it a kicking.

119
00:09:01,380 --> 00:09:04,130
Well, it's rubbish. It is absolutely
rubbish. In fact, it's so bad

120
00:09:04,180 --> 00:09:06,530
I'm not even going to bother
getting the Stig to take it

121
00:09:06,580 --> 00:09:09,170
round the track, it would just
be a complete waste of time.

122
00:09:09,220 --> 00:09:12,570
Oh, now, we ought to bring you up to
speed with the latest in car news.

123
00:09:12,620 --> 00:09:13,850
Okie-doke.

124
00:09:13,900 --> 00:09:16,850
A new Skoda coming out,
it's called the Superb.

125
00:09:16,900 --> 00:09:18,890
There it is, mainly for mini cabbers.

126
00:09:18,940 --> 00:09:21,210
But what you really need
to know is underneath,

127
00:09:21,260 --> 00:09:23,690
if you peel away the body,
it's basically a Golf, OK?

128
00:09:23,740 --> 00:09:28,890
There's another new Skoda, the Octavia
vRS, that's a Golf as well.

129
00:09:28,940 --> 00:09:31,410
New Audi, RS3 Sportback, here it is.

130
00:09:31,460 --> 00:09:33,770
That's a Golf.

131
00:09:33,820 --> 00:09:36,930
~ New Skoda Fabia.
~ Ah, is that a Golf?
~ No, that's a Polo.

132
00:09:36,980 --> 00:09:39,810
~ Is it? Oh, it's confusing.
~ It's not confusing.
~ It is.

133
00:09:39,860 --> 00:09:41,970
No, it's not, it's
really, really simple.

134
00:09:42,020 --> 00:09:45,770
All cars are basically a
Golf underneath, or a Polo,

135
00:09:45,820 --> 00:09:48,250
or a Fiat 500,

136
00:09:48,300 --> 00:09:52,250
except for this, this
is the Citroen DS5,

137
00:09:52,300 --> 00:09:55,250
that's basically a
Peugeot, underneath.

138
00:09:55,300 --> 00:09:57,530
And the Fiat 500X, that.

139
00:09:57,580 --> 00:10:01,170
~ Well, is that not a Fiat 500?
~ No, that's an Alfa Romeo.
~ Is it?

140
00:10:01,220 --> 00:10:04,410
Anyway, that's cleared up this
week's motoring news for you.

141
00:10:04,460 --> 00:10:07,090
Moving on, do you remember
that six-wheeled

142
00:10:07,140 --> 00:10:09,730
Mercedes G Wagon that I drove?
The six-wheel drive thing.

143
00:10:09,780 --> 00:10:12,130
~ Yes, in the desert, yes, yes.
~ Yeah, a massive thing.

144
00:10:12,180 --> 00:10:14,650
Well, Mercedes have now
announced that they're making

145
00:10:14,700 --> 00:10:16,410
a four-wheel version of it.

146
00:10:16,460 --> 00:10:18,490
~ Oh, there it is.
~ There, look at that.

147
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:21,530
So they've made a four-wheeled
version of the six-wheeled version

148
00:10:21,580 --> 00:10:24,930
~ of the four-wheel car they already had.
~ I think it looks great.

149
00:10:24,980 --> 00:10:28,970
Massive wheels made possible by
portal axles so it's raised up,

150
00:10:29,020 --> 00:10:31,570
it's got about 422 brake
horsepower, I think it is,

151
00:10:31,620 --> 00:10:33,530
from its V8 twin turbo.

152
00:10:33,580 --> 00:10:35,290
It is quite costly.

153
00:10:35,340 --> 00:10:37,650
£200,000 for that.

154
00:10:37,700 --> 00:10:43,770
I know, I know, but if you look closely
it's got side pipes! Oh, yes!

155
00:10:43,820 --> 00:10:46,450
And all of a sudden, ladies
and gentlemen, Richard Hammond

156
00:10:46,500 --> 00:10:48,690
has become uncomfortable
in his trousers.

157
00:10:48,740 --> 00:10:51,210
Well, I love... I do love side pipes.

158
00:10:51,260 --> 00:10:53,370
I can tell that from the
shape of your front pipe!

159
00:10:53,420 --> 00:10:55,610
Oh, is it showing? Sorry.

160
00:10:55,660 --> 00:10:59,250
Oh, now, there's a sort of
motor racing, it's called GT3,

161
00:10:59,300 --> 00:11:01,250
~ anyone seen it?
~ AUDIENCE: Yeah.

162
00:11:01,300 --> 00:11:04,410
There's a picture of a grid here.
Look at it, it's just amazing -

163
00:11:04,460 --> 00:11:08,850
Astons, McLarens, Porches, BMWs,
Nissan GT-Rs, fabulous series.

164
00:11:08,900 --> 00:11:11,570
Yeah, very exciting because
you can recognise the cars.

165
00:11:11,620 --> 00:11:14,530
But now Bentley has announced that
they're going to build a car

166
00:11:14,580 --> 00:11:17,250
that's inspired by that race series.

167
00:11:17,300 --> 00:11:19,530
It's called the GT3-R, here it is.

168
00:11:19,580 --> 00:11:23,210
And it's a sort of stripped-down,
pumped-up, road-going,

169
00:11:23,260 --> 00:11:28,250
two-seater version of the race
car. 580 horsepower, from its V8.

170
00:11:28,300 --> 00:11:29,730
I like the look of that.

171
00:11:29,780 --> 00:11:32,690
And, well, you'll like the sound,
because it's got a titanium exhaust

172
00:11:32,740 --> 00:11:35,370
that they say gives
it a baritone roar.

173
00:11:35,420 --> 00:11:36,930
So it's got Tom Jones underneath it.

174
00:11:36,980 --> 00:11:39,930
~ Basically, they've strapped Tom Jones...
~ Poor Tom, "Whoa!"

175
00:11:39,980 --> 00:11:42,890
~ That's how it sounds.
~ Aston Martin have got a very similar

176
00:11:42,940 --> 00:11:45,130
sort of thing, called
a Vantage V12 GT3.

177
00:11:45,180 --> 00:11:46,250
AUDIENCE: Oooh!

178
00:11:46,300 --> 00:11:49,290
~ Exactly, whoa, that is a V12, obviously.
~ Does look quite cool.

179
00:11:49,340 --> 00:11:51,810
600 horsepower, so 20
more than the Bentley

180
00:11:51,860 --> 00:11:53,610
and it's half a tonne lighter.

181
00:11:53,660 --> 00:11:57,530
That is properly blowing
my frock up, that thing.

182
00:11:57,580 --> 00:12:00,490
It really is. Philosophy news...

183
00:12:00,540 --> 00:12:05,050
Everybody - no, don't groan, because
I know it sounds dreary but...

184
00:12:05,100 --> 00:12:08,930
~ driverless cars are coming, as we know.
~ Yeah.

185
00:12:08,980 --> 00:12:10,690
And somebody pointed out this week,

186
00:12:10,740 --> 00:12:12,650
and I think it's rather a good point,

187
00:12:12,700 --> 00:12:16,250
that they will have to make, from
time to time, ethical decisions.

188
00:12:16,300 --> 00:12:19,290
What, like, should we
cancel Third World debt?

189
00:12:19,340 --> 00:12:21,890
No, James, not that. You're
driving along, OK?

190
00:12:21,940 --> 00:12:24,930
And you're heading towards an accident.
You're not driving, you're

191
00:12:24,980 --> 00:12:27,650
sitting there. You're heading
towards an accident, it's going

192
00:12:27,700 --> 00:12:30,330
to be fatal. The only solution
is to swerve onto the pavement,

193
00:12:30,380 --> 00:12:32,610
but there are two pedestrians there.

194
00:12:32,660 --> 00:12:34,930
What does the car do?

195
00:12:34,980 --> 00:12:37,330
Wow, is this the Moral
Maze or something?

196
00:12:37,380 --> 00:12:39,010
No, it's a genuine thing.

197
00:12:39,060 --> 00:12:43,010
Cos basically you will have bought
a car that must be programmed,

198
00:12:43,060 --> 00:12:46,650
in certain circumstances,
to kill you. It will go,

199
00:12:46,700 --> 00:12:49,410
"Well, there's two there, there's
only one person in me,

200
00:12:49,460 --> 00:12:52,370
"I'm going to kill him." And you'll
just have to sit there, as the lorry

201
00:12:52,420 --> 00:12:55,290
~ comes and there's nothing you can do.
~ Well, maybe driverless cars

202
00:12:55,340 --> 00:12:58,210
will have to come with,
like, an override button.

203
00:12:58,260 --> 00:13:01,490
Just a big button with "ME" on
it. So, in a crash - save me!

204
00:13:01,540 --> 00:13:04,170
~ Just hit that.
~ Or maybe it could have a sliding scale.

205
00:13:04,220 --> 00:13:07,010
So you can say, look, if there's
a load of children on the pavement

206
00:13:07,060 --> 00:13:10,540
obviously don't run them
down, but cyclists...

207
00:13:12,580 --> 00:13:16,330
We are in dark territory
here, aren't we?

208
00:13:16,380 --> 00:13:19,930
Well, the interesting thing
is, all of us are programmed,

209
00:13:19,980 --> 00:13:22,530
because we're humans, cos
we're animals, basically,

210
00:13:22,580 --> 00:13:25,290
to look after ourselves.
Self-preservation always kicks in

211
00:13:25,340 --> 00:13:28,850
~ and you will swerve away from danger.
~ Not necessarily.

212
00:13:28,900 --> 00:13:32,010
Oh, well, now you say that, but
recently scientists conducted

213
00:13:32,060 --> 00:13:34,570
an absolutely awful, genuinely
awful experiment,

214
00:13:34,620 --> 00:13:36,370
but with a very interesting result.

215
00:13:36,420 --> 00:13:39,370
They got a load of monkeys with their
babies and put them in a box.

216
00:13:39,420 --> 00:13:41,970
And then they heated the floor
up - this actually happened -

217
00:13:42,020 --> 00:13:44,010
I, you know, I'm just reporting.

218
00:13:44,060 --> 00:13:46,530
They heated the floor up till
it became really unbearable

219
00:13:46,580 --> 00:13:50,770
and all of the monkeys picked
up their babies and held them.

220
00:13:50,820 --> 00:13:54,090
But when the floor got hotter and
hotter until it was absolutely

221
00:13:54,140 --> 00:13:57,610
unbearable, every one of them put
the babies down and stood on them.

222
00:13:57,660 --> 00:13:59,690
GASPING AND GIGGLING

223
00:13:59,740 --> 00:14:02,250
I'm... I'm surprised...

224
00:14:02,300 --> 00:14:05,530
I'm surprised you didn't save this
for the Christmas show, mate.

225
00:14:05,580 --> 00:14:06,890
LAUGHTER

226
00:14:06,940 --> 00:14:10,050
What a lovely story,
what a nice tale(!)

227
00:14:10,100 --> 00:14:11,370
I love a story!

228
00:14:11,420 --> 00:14:14,450
I'm just saying, these driverless
cars, everybody goes,

229
00:14:14,500 --> 00:14:16,610
"Aren't they clever? They
can stop at red lights."

230
00:14:16,660 --> 00:14:18,890
They are going to have to
face all sorts of things,

231
00:14:18,940 --> 00:14:20,210
like who do I kill now?

232
00:14:20,260 --> 00:14:23,290
We are programmed to look after
ourselves and these driverless cars

233
00:14:23,340 --> 00:14:25,610
are going to be programmed
to do the maths and say,

234
00:14:25,660 --> 00:14:28,170
"A lot of people over there,
I'm going to kill you."

235
00:14:28,220 --> 00:14:30,570
And whether to stand
on a baby monkey.

236
00:14:30,620 --> 00:14:32,890
LAUGHTER

237
00:14:32,940 --> 00:14:36,810
Now, Brooklands, world's first
purpose-built racetrack,

238
00:14:36,860 --> 00:14:38,930
~ do you remember it?
~ Well, no. He will.

239
00:14:38,980 --> 00:14:40,410
Oh, yeah, he will, obviously.

240
00:14:40,460 --> 00:14:42,770
We've got some footage of
it here to remind everyone.

241
00:14:42,820 --> 00:14:44,810
This was just outside
London, and look at it,

242
00:14:44,860 --> 00:14:47,650
everybody walked fast and were
in black and white in those days.

243
00:14:47,700 --> 00:14:51,570
And you went unbelievable - look
at this, 120mph on the banking.

244
00:14:51,620 --> 00:14:54,850
And then there's James May,
look, in his pedal car.

245
00:14:54,900 --> 00:14:57,130
And then it was just fantastic.

246
00:14:57,180 --> 00:15:01,170
But the war started, they built an
aeroplane factory on the circuit

247
00:15:01,220 --> 00:15:02,770
and that was the end of that.

248
00:15:02,820 --> 00:15:05,930
Ever since, there's been a group
of enthusiasts who want Brooklands

249
00:15:05,980 --> 00:15:09,130
to reopen, and last week, actually,
they were given a grant

250
00:15:09,180 --> 00:15:12,210
by the lottery people
of £4.6 million.

251
00:15:12,260 --> 00:15:15,570
And I just think that's going to be
brilliant. Get that back - Astons,

252
00:15:15,620 --> 00:15:17,890
Bentleys belting around
at the weekend,

253
00:15:17,940 --> 00:15:21,850
Fotherington Sorbet wheel-to-wheel
with the Duke of Wyndham.

254
00:15:21,900 --> 00:15:24,450
It's a very good idea for an
appealing Sunday afternoon,

255
00:15:24,500 --> 00:15:26,890
watching the toffs kill themselves.

256
00:15:26,940 --> 00:15:29,210
You just pop down the A3
on a Sunday afternoon,

257
00:15:29,260 --> 00:15:32,370
"Let's go and watch the Earl
of Bradford's head come off."

258
00:15:32,420 --> 00:15:35,330
~ How much did you say they'd been given?
~ £4.6 million.

259
00:15:35,380 --> 00:15:38,330
Well, that's not enough, is it? The
shopping centre next to our office

260
00:15:38,380 --> 00:15:41,690
~ cost one and a half billion.
~ Yes, exactly, it isn't very much,

261
00:15:41,740 --> 00:15:43,730
you're quite right,
well spotted, Hammond.

262
00:15:43,780 --> 00:15:46,810
In fact, all they can afford
to do with that is rebuild

263
00:15:46,860 --> 00:15:49,370
the start/finish straight.

264
00:15:49,420 --> 00:15:52,490
Hang on, just the start/finish
straight of a race circuit

265
00:15:52,540 --> 00:15:54,450
~ is not much use in itself.
~ No.

266
00:15:54,500 --> 00:15:58,450
Unless they spend all 4.6
million on lottery tickets.

267
00:15:58,500 --> 00:16:01,530
It's lottery money, they can take the
grant, spend it on lottery tickets

268
00:16:01,580 --> 00:16:05,130
~ and win a lot more.
~ Good thinking from Richard Hammond there,

269
00:16:05,180 --> 00:16:08,330
he's saved motor racing
for the nation.

270
00:16:08,380 --> 00:16:12,330
Now, I know this is a car show,
but please bear with us,

271
00:16:12,380 --> 00:16:13,970
because I want to talk about this.

272
00:16:14,020 --> 00:16:17,490
It's one of those watches
that's worn by people

273
00:16:17,540 --> 00:16:19,330
who play golf and do business.

274
00:16:19,380 --> 00:16:24,250
And they're always banging on about
these pins that you can see here.

275
00:16:24,300 --> 00:16:28,610
Yeah, they say that if they pull
those pins out, the watch will send

276
00:16:28,660 --> 00:16:31,290
their precise position
to a team of professionals

277
00:16:31,340 --> 00:16:33,450
who will come and rescue them.

278
00:16:33,500 --> 00:16:36,890
So, if they're out climbing a mountain
or rowing across an ocean...

279
00:16:36,940 --> 00:16:39,650
Which they aren't, cos they're
playing golf and doing business.

280
00:16:39,700 --> 00:16:42,450
But if they were doing those things,
and something went wrong,

281
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:46,570
~ then thanks to their watch, they'd be OK.
~ Ah, but would they?

282
00:16:46,620 --> 00:16:50,250
To find out, the producers decided
that one of us should be dumped

283
00:16:50,300 --> 00:16:53,410
somewhere with minimal kit,
with virtually no food,

284
00:16:53,460 --> 00:16:58,020
somewhere very, very remote
to see if the system works.

285
00:17:34,020 --> 00:17:35,360
Well...

286
00:17:37,580 --> 00:17:39,450
.. that's it.

287
00:17:39,500 --> 00:17:43,650
I am now marooned here,

288
00:17:43,700 --> 00:17:45,900
wherever the hell here is.

289
00:17:48,740 --> 00:17:50,280
Bloody hell.

290
00:17:53,300 --> 00:17:57,370
My only hope now is my watch.

291
00:17:57,420 --> 00:18:00,100
So... it's time.

292
00:18:01,420 --> 00:18:03,220
Undo this.

293
00:18:04,820 --> 00:18:06,850
There.

294
00:18:06,900 --> 00:18:09,240
And then pull that bit out...

295
00:18:10,460 --> 00:18:12,380
And that's it done.

296
00:18:15,300 --> 00:18:19,450
Pulling those pins activates a
distress signal that's picked up

297
00:18:19,500 --> 00:18:22,370
by a LEOSAR - Low Earth
Polar Orbit Satellite -

298
00:18:22,420 --> 00:18:25,130
which then forwards
my exact coordinates

299
00:18:25,180 --> 00:18:27,410
to a central command centre.

300
00:18:27,460 --> 00:18:30,690
The team here then scramble
the nearest highly-trained

301
00:18:30,740 --> 00:18:35,060
search and rescue unit, who arrive
at my location within hours.

302
00:18:38,100 --> 00:18:43,490
Sadly, however, today the scramble
command has not been sent

303
00:18:43,540 --> 00:18:46,330
to a highly-trained search
and rescue unit.

304
00:18:46,380 --> 00:18:48,620
HAMMOND PANTS

305
00:18:57,660 --> 00:18:59,090
.. running on petrol.

306
00:18:59,140 --> 00:19:02,250
It's a brilliant idea, and I'm
not sure the Ferrari does that.

307
00:19:02,300 --> 00:19:05,050
I think it does, but I think they're
just being honest about it cos

308
00:19:05,100 --> 00:19:08,010
they're recognising that it's a
means of improving the efficiency.

309
00:19:08,060 --> 00:19:10,770
~ Is that your bag ringing?
~ BEEPING

310
00:19:10,820 --> 00:19:14,050
Oh, I think this is the signal
from our esteemed colleague

311
00:19:14,100 --> 00:19:16,290
~ Richard Hammond.
~ Is it? Where is he?

312
00:19:16,340 --> 00:19:20,210
Wait a minute. He would appear
to be in... Africa, is it?

313
00:19:20,260 --> 00:19:22,130
Let's have a look.

314
00:19:22,620 --> 00:19:25,810
No, I think you'll find that is...

315
00:19:25,860 --> 00:19:27,450
Canada.

316
00:19:27,500 --> 00:19:30,090
Specifically the Rockies.

317
00:19:30,140 --> 00:19:33,530
Crikey! Um... actually,
that is quite serious.

318
00:19:33,580 --> 00:19:38,010
We really do need to get on
this, James, so, excuse me...

319
00:19:38,060 --> 00:19:40,460
could we see the pudding menu?

320
00:19:41,580 --> 00:19:42,980
Right...

321
00:19:43,700 --> 00:19:47,540
.. that bit suspends off this bit.

322
00:19:51,060 --> 00:19:54,140
That watch transmits for 24 hours.

323
00:19:55,980 --> 00:19:57,850
And then that's it.

324
00:20:00,580 --> 00:20:05,410
Right, so this is the
mountain, there's my tent.

325
00:20:05,460 --> 00:20:08,610
Mountain, trees, hills.
This is all we are.

326
00:20:08,660 --> 00:20:10,610
There's a cameraman,
a sound recordist

327
00:20:10,660 --> 00:20:13,650
and a bloke from the office
and he's just a media luvvie.

328
00:20:13,700 --> 00:20:17,490
I know you think there's
a five-star hotel

329
00:20:17,540 --> 00:20:20,370
just down there, but there's not.

330
00:20:20,420 --> 00:20:23,720
Nothing else. There's no
survival experts here.

331
00:20:24,060 --> 00:20:27,010
Fact of the matter is I'm
completely stuck until

332
00:20:27,060 --> 00:20:29,660
Yogi the boar and Boo-Boo get here.

333
00:20:31,780 --> 00:20:33,770
Knowing we were his only hope,

334
00:20:33,820 --> 00:20:36,530
we had some important
decisions to make.

335
00:20:36,580 --> 00:20:40,690
Raunchy apple fritters sounds quite
interesting. Or pancake with cheese.

336
00:20:40,740 --> 00:20:42,410
James, James, James.

337
00:20:42,460 --> 00:20:45,850
You know in the colonies, Australia,
South Africa, America,

338
00:20:45,900 --> 00:20:49,650
~ Canada and so on, everybody
loves pick-up trucks, yes?
~ Yes.

339
00:20:49,700 --> 00:20:53,530
Well, why don't we get a pick-up
truck to go and rescue Hammond in?

340
00:20:53,580 --> 00:20:56,010
Because pick-up trucks generally
only have two seats

341
00:20:56,060 --> 00:20:58,650
and there would be three of
us when we've rescued him.

342
00:20:58,700 --> 00:21:01,370
Why don't we get two pick-up
trucks, one for you, one for me?

343
00:21:01,420 --> 00:21:04,130
It would A, increase our
chances of finding him,

344
00:21:04,180 --> 00:21:07,970
~ and B, there'd be a seat to get him back in.
~ But...

345
00:21:08,020 --> 00:21:13,850
In Thunderbirds, inevitably
1 and 2 kind of went first,

346
00:21:13,900 --> 00:21:15,810
~ didn't they, always.
~ Yeah.

347
00:21:15,860 --> 00:21:20,250
Alan and... No, not Alan - who
drove Thunderbird 1? Scott.

348
00:21:20,300 --> 00:21:22,490
~ Virgil.
~ No, Virgil was 2.

349
00:21:22,540 --> 00:21:25,810
~ Was he 2?
~ Scott was 1,

350
00:21:25,860 --> 00:21:27,890
Virgil was 2, Alan was 3,

351
00:21:27,940 --> 00:21:30,100
~ Gordon was 4.
~ Gordon!

352
00:21:31,180 --> 00:21:34,810
In Canada, the temperature
was a bitter minus 10,

353
00:21:34,860 --> 00:21:37,400
so I urgently needed some warmth.

354
00:21:44,940 --> 00:21:48,540
What would have been wrong
with giving me a lighter?

355
00:21:49,220 --> 00:21:51,210
Can't get my fire lit.

356
00:21:51,260 --> 00:21:53,450
Cold beans.

357
00:21:53,500 --> 00:21:56,100
They're a bit frozen in the middle.

358
00:22:01,260 --> 00:22:03,250
'Having finished our lunch...'

359
00:22:03,300 --> 00:22:05,570
I'm not sure about the red, you know.

360
00:22:05,620 --> 00:22:08,920
'.. we went to book some
flights to Vancouver.'

361
00:22:09,780 --> 00:22:13,250
~ OK, you've actually just missed
the last flight out today.
~ Have we?

362
00:22:13,300 --> 00:22:16,170
~ Yeah.
~ Oh, what a rotten bit of luck.
Shall we go and get another drink?

363
00:22:16,220 --> 00:22:19,570
There's a Delta One that leaves
at ten o'clock tomorrow morning.

364
00:22:19,620 --> 00:22:22,290
Don't like Delta's seat upholstery.

365
00:22:22,340 --> 00:22:24,570
Would you go from Manchester?

366
00:22:24,620 --> 00:22:27,890
Manchester, no, you know, this
is the BBC, it think it would be

367
00:22:27,940 --> 00:22:31,170
idiotic to go to Manchester, I
mean, that would be just stupid.

368
00:22:31,220 --> 00:22:33,570
There's Lufthansa.

369
00:22:33,620 --> 00:22:35,330
Stewardesses wear trousers.

370
00:22:35,380 --> 00:22:38,490
~ There's one from Gatwick
which goes via Calgary if...
~ Gatwick?

371
00:22:38,540 --> 00:22:40,330
~ He doesn't like Gatwick.
~ I hate Gatwick.

372
00:22:40,380 --> 00:22:43,300
WOLF HOWLS

373
00:22:49,380 --> 00:22:51,380
Out there somewhere...

374
00:22:52,340 --> 00:22:54,610
.. there are...

375
00:22:54,660 --> 00:22:55,930
bears.

376
00:22:57,180 --> 00:23:00,060
As many as 180,000 black bears.

377
00:23:01,300 --> 00:23:05,000
I can't remember what it
was, about 15,000 grizzlies.

378
00:23:08,860 --> 00:23:10,570
ICE RATTLES

379
00:23:10,620 --> 00:23:12,020
Freezing.

380
00:23:16,580 --> 00:23:20,810
In the morning I was cold and
exhausted from lack of sleep,

381
00:23:20,860 --> 00:23:23,500
but most of all, I was anxious.

382
00:23:27,740 --> 00:23:29,410
Any minute now.

383
00:23:30,540 --> 00:23:32,080
Any minute.

384
00:23:34,220 --> 00:23:36,560
I mean, they've had 24 hours.

385
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:40,700
I mean... 24 hours.

386
00:23:42,060 --> 00:23:45,780
You can get anywhere in the
world in 24 hours, surely.

387
00:23:50,500 --> 00:23:52,980
Where the hell are they?

388
00:24:02,220 --> 00:24:04,490
~ I can't remember...
~ James.

389
00:24:05,780 --> 00:24:08,690
~ It's stopped beeping.
~ Well, yeah, it would.

390
00:24:08,740 --> 00:24:11,730
~ Why would it?
~ Cos the watch thing only
transmits the distress signal

391
00:24:11,780 --> 00:24:16,050
for 24 hours, then
the battery runs out.

392
00:24:16,100 --> 00:24:18,170
~ Seriously?
~ Well, yeah, it's only...

393
00:24:18,220 --> 00:24:19,930
Well, did you make a
note of where he was?

394
00:24:19,980 --> 00:24:22,920
Well, no, I didn't.
You've got the thing.

395
00:24:23,740 --> 00:24:27,450
Well, I... I remember he
was on something called...

396
00:24:27,500 --> 00:24:31,530
I think it was Wolf Mountain,
and you go up Bear Pass.

397
00:24:31,580 --> 00:24:33,010
Sounds grizzly.

398
00:24:33,060 --> 00:24:35,850
~ HE LAUGHS
~ That was a good joke.

399
00:24:35,900 --> 00:24:39,050
No, actually, do you know the
biggest problem is not bears

400
00:24:39,100 --> 00:24:40,690
and wolves...

401
00:24:40,740 --> 00:24:42,610
cougars. Loads of cougars.

402
00:24:42,660 --> 00:24:45,450
~ Well, that's all right, then.
~ No, not that sort of cougar.

403
00:24:45,500 --> 00:24:47,690
Actually, a "Grrrr!"
That sort of cougar.

404
00:24:47,740 --> 00:24:50,840
~ Oh, you mean like a big cat thing?
~ HE SNARLS

405
00:24:52,300 --> 00:24:56,210
As I couldn't move from the spot
where the watch had transmitted

406
00:24:56,260 --> 00:24:57,650
the distress signal,

407
00:24:57,700 --> 00:25:01,780
I was hard at work trying to make
my life here more comfortable.

408
00:25:08,500 --> 00:25:10,290
I want somewhere to sit.

409
00:25:10,340 --> 00:25:13,840
I can't sit on the snow
so I'm building a shelter.

410
00:25:18,940 --> 00:25:20,820
HE STRIKES FLINT

411
00:25:22,780 --> 00:25:24,650
Spark, you bastard.

412
00:25:25,620 --> 00:25:28,820
There we go, we have fire.

413
00:25:30,140 --> 00:25:34,820
'And with my supplies dwindling,
I also needed to think about food.'

414
00:25:36,580 --> 00:25:38,450
"Animals for food.

415
00:25:39,940 --> 00:25:42,050
"Guinea pigs.

416
00:25:42,100 --> 00:25:44,490
"All animals can be a
source of nourishment.

417
00:25:44,540 --> 00:25:48,740
"A few, including worms and insects,
can be collected with little skill."

418
00:25:59,260 --> 00:26:04,130
I'm bored, I'm cold, I'm unhappy,
I'm hungry, I'm scared.

419
00:26:04,180 --> 00:26:06,330
Ahh! Ahh!

420
00:26:06,380 --> 00:26:08,610
And I don't want to be wearing a hat!

421
00:26:08,660 --> 00:26:10,660
Just for a minute. Oh.

422
00:26:12,700 --> 00:26:16,210
'To alleviate the boredom,
and stave off the cold,

423
00:26:16,260 --> 00:26:19,900
'I tried to make some
SAS-style pine needle tea.'

424
00:26:22,540 --> 00:26:23,680
Ah!

425
00:26:24,700 --> 00:26:27,250
Ow! Ow!

426
00:26:27,300 --> 00:26:31,060
Ow! Where are they, just where?!

427
00:26:37,220 --> 00:26:41,930
'Unfortunately, we were a little
bit delayed at Vancouver Airport...'

428
00:26:41,980 --> 00:26:43,650
Yes, of course.

429
00:26:44,020 --> 00:26:46,690
'But eventually we made
it to the car park,

430
00:26:46,740 --> 00:26:50,300
'where our pick-up truck rescue
vehicles were waiting.'

431
00:27:09,420 --> 00:27:10,890
~ James.
~ Yeah.

432
00:27:10,940 --> 00:27:13,730
That's not a light - that's
a collapsed sun, isn't it?

433
00:27:13,780 --> 00:27:15,530
Yeah, never mind that, look.

434
00:27:15,580 --> 00:27:18,690
Mine is actually... comes
up to my nipples.

435
00:27:18,740 --> 00:27:22,210
I didn't realise it was... And do
you know what the other thing is?

436
00:27:22,260 --> 00:27:25,210
If I actually find Richard Hammond,
I'm not going to see him, am I?

437
00:27:25,260 --> 00:27:26,690
I'll just run straight over him.

438
00:27:26,740 --> 00:27:29,050
Have you noticed something
else about mine?

439
00:27:29,100 --> 00:27:32,530
This entire vehicle is
a transportation device

440
00:27:32,580 --> 00:27:34,490
for its own spare wheel, look.

441
00:27:34,540 --> 00:27:37,450
~ That's all the back's for!
~ That's really stupid.

442
00:27:37,500 --> 00:27:39,650
~ It's preposter...
~ Look at the size of it.
~ Look at it!

443
00:27:39,700 --> 00:27:42,130
Anyway, listen, we've got
everything we need here.

444
00:27:42,180 --> 00:27:44,730
I've got a big warm coat,
I've got a massive car,

445
00:27:44,780 --> 00:27:46,810
a rough idea of where
Richard Hammond is.

446
00:27:46,860 --> 00:27:48,650
Yeah, so let's go...

447
00:27:48,700 --> 00:27:52,050
into Vancouver, get a hotel,
good night's rest,

448
00:27:52,100 --> 00:27:54,240
get rid of this jet lag.

449
00:28:00,140 --> 00:28:02,650
It's not funny. I don't know what...

450
00:28:02,700 --> 00:28:05,240
They've got to get here tomorrow.

451
00:28:06,020 --> 00:28:07,780
Morning. Early.

452
00:28:20,100 --> 00:28:22,210
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

453
00:28:22,260 --> 00:28:24,730
Um...

454
00:28:24,780 --> 00:28:27,170
Hold on.

455
00:28:27,220 --> 00:28:28,770
Hold on a minute.

456
00:28:28,820 --> 00:28:31,290
Can I just make something clear?

457
00:28:32,020 --> 00:28:35,650
That's the first time I've seen
this film and, um, I'm sorry,

458
00:28:35,700 --> 00:28:37,650
you two went into Vancouver.

459
00:28:37,700 --> 00:28:39,970
~ Well, yes.
~ To get rid of your jet lag.
~ Yes.

460
00:28:40,020 --> 00:28:41,530
No, tiredness kills, Hammond.

461
00:28:41,580 --> 00:28:44,170
~ Haven't you seen those
signs on the motorway?
~ Exactly.

462
00:28:44,220 --> 00:28:47,050
What annoys me as well here is
that you chose to do it in big

463
00:28:47,100 --> 00:28:49,570
~ American pick-up trucks.
~ Well, that's a good idea,

464
00:28:49,620 --> 00:28:52,690
because we hardly ever do big American
pick-up trucks on Top Gear.

465
00:28:52,740 --> 00:28:54,690
I know, I'm always
campaigning to do them.

466
00:28:54,740 --> 00:28:56,130
I know, and in part two of the film,

467
00:28:56,180 --> 00:28:59,610
we do them extensively on many
different types of terrain.

468
00:28:59,660 --> 00:29:01,810
Yes! Without me! LAUGHTER

469
00:29:01,860 --> 00:29:04,450
Oh, this is unbelievable! I've
never heard such ingratitude.

470
00:29:04,500 --> 00:29:08,610
5,400 miles we travelled
to come and rescue you.

471
00:29:08,660 --> 00:29:11,890
~ In slow motion.
~ Yeah, but we thought you liked tenting!

472
00:29:11,940 --> 00:29:14,690
I do, in the Lake District
where there's a bit of drizzle

473
00:29:14,740 --> 00:29:16,210
and you can go out for some cake,

474
00:29:16,260 --> 00:29:20,450
not on top of a mountain at minus
ten, surrounded by bears!

