..James and I had BOTH decided
to rip out our own fingernails.

945
00:56:44,260 --> 00:56:45,570
Ow!

946
00:56:45,620 --> 00:56:46,940
Ow!

947
00:56:49,500 --> 00:56:51,970
This made progress MUCH easier.

948
00:56:53,020 --> 00:56:57,850
That feels good. Temperatures and
pressures still in the green.

949
00:56:57,900 --> 00:57:01,130
With snow chains fitted, you're
supposed to be gentle,

950
00:57:01,180 --> 00:57:05,370
but luckily my colleague doesn't
know what that means.

951
00:57:05,420 --> 00:57:07,140
RATTLING

952
00:57:08,420 --> 00:57:10,290
Dig and claw, dig and claw.

953
00:57:10,340 --> 00:57:11,770
Come on! Digging.

954
00:57:11,820 --> 00:57:13,850
Damn and blast!

955
00:57:13,900 --> 00:57:16,580
ENGINE WHINES

956
00:57:20,900 --> 00:57:22,650
Come on!

957
00:57:22,700 --> 00:57:24,610
COME ON!

958
00:57:24,660 --> 00:57:28,940
No, you want to do this, you DON'T
want Richard Hammond in you.

959
00:57:30,500 --> 00:57:32,500
~ HISSING
~ Oh, no!

960
00:57:33,900 --> 00:57:36,100
The news was grim.

961
00:57:38,140 --> 00:57:39,700
BLEEP!

962
00:57:46,700 --> 00:57:50,810
You are genuinely a bit of
a desperado here, Silverado.

963
00:57:50,860 --> 00:57:52,400
Loving that.

964
00:57:53,220 --> 00:57:54,770
And loving that as well.

965
00:57:54,820 --> 00:57:57,850
I'm still coming, Richard Hammond.

966
00:57:57,900 --> 00:58:00,500
And you know what? So was I.

967
00:58:03,820 --> 00:58:06,770
We are under way. Three
wheels on my wagon

968
00:58:06,820 --> 00:58:09,090
and I AM still rolling along.

969
00:58:09,140 --> 00:58:10,940
Come on, machine.

970
00:58:12,300 --> 00:58:15,300
Where the hell is James
May? Where is May?

971
00:58:17,260 --> 00:58:18,930
Bit of beans there.

972
00:58:18,980 --> 00:58:21,850
Slightly less beans
there for the climb.

973
00:58:23,100 --> 00:58:25,620
ENGINE ROARS

974
00:58:27,420 --> 00:58:31,100
That's an engine. It's not
a plane, it's a car. It's...

975
00:58:38,300 --> 00:58:40,300
That's got to be them!

976
00:58:41,300 --> 00:58:44,500
YELLS: Where the bloody
hell have they been?!

977
00:58:44,620 --> 00:58:46,890
Come on. Do it.

978
00:58:46,940 --> 00:58:48,570
Claw.

979
00:58:48,620 --> 00:58:51,130
Stop panicking, just...

980
00:58:51,180 --> 00:58:53,410
ease it off.

981
00:58:53,460 --> 00:58:55,210
Really struggling.

982
00:58:55,260 --> 00:58:57,370
Really struggling here.

983
00:58:57,420 --> 00:58:58,820
Come on!

984
00:59:03,380 --> 00:59:06,730
It's Hammond! Hammond is THERE!

985
00:59:06,780 --> 00:59:09,530
How can it have taken that long?!

986
00:59:09,580 --> 00:59:15,330
May, bad news. You're going to have
to take Hammond BACK to Vancouver.

987
00:59:15,380 --> 00:59:18,770
That's a powerful vehicle,
that is a go-anywhere car.

988
00:59:18,820 --> 00:59:21,530
~ So where the
~ BLEEP
~ have you been?

989
00:59:21,580 --> 00:59:25,650
And he's in an appalling
temper, absolutely shocking.

990
00:59:25,700 --> 00:59:28,860
Where are you going? Well, now what?!

991
00:59:29,900 --> 00:59:32,370
Oh, that's your rescue, is it?!

992
00:59:35,540 --> 00:59:38,050
CHEERING AND APPLAUSE

993
00:59:38,100 --> 00:59:40,890
COMMENTS DROWNED OUT BY APPLAUSE

994
00:59:40,940 --> 00:59:42,380
Hold on.

995
00:59:43,500 --> 00:59:46,050
THAT was shocking!

996
00:59:46,100 --> 00:59:49,010
I have seen Thunderbirds
and I never saw Alan

997
00:59:49,060 --> 00:59:52,050
flying along, listening to Boston,
eating a bar of chocolate.

998
00:59:52,100 --> 00:59:53,850
~ No, you say that...
~ Neither did I see

999
00:59:53,900 --> 00:59:56,130
Virgil suggesting they
stop for a cappuccino,

1000
00:59:56,180 --> 00:59:58,410
they were both focused
on the job in hand.

1001
00:59:58,460 --> 01:00:03,730
Yes. But in that film, we did prove
that your watch system works

1002
01:00:03,780 --> 01:00:05,970
and both James and I

1003
01:00:06,020 --> 01:00:08,930
completely fell in love with
our pick-up trucks, didn't we?

1004
01:00:08,980 --> 01:00:10,490
Yeah, no, this is a very good point.

1005
01:00:10,540 --> 01:00:12,290
Because, let's be
honest, for 12 years

1006
01:00:12,340 --> 01:00:14,890
we've looked down our noses at
big, American pick-up trucks.

1007
01:00:14,940 --> 01:00:17,330
But having spent quite
a few days in them,

1008
01:00:17,380 --> 01:00:19,050
we ended up completely besotted.

1009
01:00:19,100 --> 01:00:21,370
It's the value that staggers me.

1010
01:00:21,420 --> 01:00:25,810
Because American pick-up trucks are
exempt from the gas guzzler tax,

1011
01:00:25,860 --> 01:00:27,810
they are SPECTACULARLY cheap.

1012
01:00:27,860 --> 01:00:29,370
Yeah. I'm surprised actually

1013
01:00:29,420 --> 01:00:31,730
there aren't more people
importing them over here.

1014
01:00:31,780 --> 01:00:35,010
Yeah, well, I think the problem
is a car, vehicle I should say,

1015
01:00:35,060 --> 01:00:37,570
this size wouldn't really
work in Britain.

1016
01:00:37,620 --> 01:00:40,130
And there's another problem.
Excuse me, Hammond.

1017
01:00:40,180 --> 01:00:42,210
I think if you put
something in the back,

1018
01:00:42,260 --> 01:00:44,010
every time you pull up
at a set of red lights

1019
01:00:44,060 --> 01:00:45,530
someone is going to nick it.

1020
01:00:45,580 --> 01:00:47,530
Yeah, you're dead right.
You're dead right.

1021
01:00:47,580 --> 01:00:51,330
But even so, I maintain my
Silverado, it was brilliant.

1022
01:00:51,380 --> 01:00:53,210
Well, it was, James,
but let's be honest,

1023
01:00:53,260 --> 01:00:55,930
it didn't actually reach the
top of the mountain, did it?

1024
01:00:55,980 --> 01:00:57,530
No, I wasn't going to mention that.

1025
01:00:57,580 --> 01:00:59,970
Actually, just before the end
it did break a driveshaft.

1026
01:01:00,020 --> 01:01:02,210
Yeah, I did wonder if you
were going to mention that,

1027
01:01:02,260 --> 01:01:03,530
because it wasn't IN the film

1028
01:01:03,580 --> 01:01:06,930
In the end, neither Thunderbird
Fat nor Thunderbird Slow

1029
01:01:06,980 --> 01:01:09,930
~ actually rescued me.
~ That is true.

1030
01:01:09,980 --> 01:01:12,250
No, an actual rescue person
had to come and save me.

1031
01:01:12,300 --> 01:01:16,650
And can I just talk about the four
days - FOUR DAYS - of misery

1032
01:01:16,700 --> 01:01:19,410
I endured whilst you two
dawdled from breakfast

1033
01:01:19,460 --> 01:01:21,410
to breakfast in your heated trucks.

1034
01:01:21,460 --> 01:01:22,810
No, I'm sorry, there isn't time.

1035
01:01:22,860 --> 01:01:25,290
And on that bombshell
we really must end.

1036
01:01:25,340 --> 01:01:27,930
Thank you so much for
watching. Good night!

